00460769,-0.03838266,-0.02466891,-0.00484896,0.04943285,0.00562144,-0.04004284,-0.01262728,-0.00793212,0.02806395,-0.01361138,0.07910980,0.02086266,-0.01551192,0.03617314,-0.03760037,0.03665414,-0.01472380,0.05969577,-0.09134825,0.03375727,0.03732891,-0.05948774,-0.00292770,0.01718138,-0.05489086,-0.02747774,0.00372716,-0.07447024,0.00210498,-0.00684160,0.05922392,0.01690995,0.00923997,-0.02164041,-0.04319631,0.04581310,0.07845881,-0.07341948,0.13265836,-0.00623431,0.01401154]',E'Advanced installation\n\nThe Update Center only allows the installation of the most recently released\nversion of a plugin. In cases where an older release of the plugin is desired,\na Jenkins administrator can download an older `.hpi` archive and manually\ninstall that on the Jenkins controller.\n\nJenkins stores plugins it has downloaded in the `plugins` directory with a `.jpi` suffix, whether the plugins originally had a `.jpi` or an `.hpi` suffix.\n\nIf an administrator manually copies a plugin archive into the `plugins` directory, it should be named with a `.jpi` suffix to match the file names used by plugins installed from the update center.','{"source": "jenkins", "version": "2.4", "language": "groovy", "title": "Plugins.Adoc", "section_title": "plugins.adoc", "url": "https://github.com/jenkins-infra/jenkins.io/blob/master/content/doc/book/managing/plugins.adoc", "topics": "jenkins,ci,pipeline,plugins.adoc", "categories": "devops,ci,automation"}');
